  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: fcf7219bab7fe46a1ad266029b2fee19, type: 3}
  m_Name: Readme - 06
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  icon: {fileID: 0}
  title: Readme - 06
  sections:
  - heading: Animation Clip
    text: You can animate any serialized field within an Animation Clip. A common
      use of this is animating the sprite associated with an object. The clip provides
      information about values and timing on specific frames, known as key frames.
      When working with values such as floats, you can also determine the curve used
      to interpolate between values on non-key frames.
    linkText: Animation Clips
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/AnimationClips.html
  - heading: 'Animator '
    text: An animator is a sort of controller for an object that can help manage
      a number of animation clips within a state machine. Each node in the graph
      is associated with an animation, and can be connected to other nodes with transitions.
      Transitions can be given conditions using parameters that belong to the animator.
      These parameters can be manipulated through code to indicate the desired state
      to the animator.
    linkText: Animator Controller
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/class-AnimatorController.html
  - heading: StateMachineBehaviours
    text: StateMachineBehaviours can be used to execute code during certain points
      within a node's lifecycle. This can be useful to trigger conditions at appropriate
      times, such as indicating the start or end of a particular state, or even manipulating
      the gameobject or other components.
    linkText: State Machine Behaviour Reference
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/StateMachineBehaviours.html
  - heading: Sprite Import Settings
    text: When importing sprites, there are a few key settings that make a difference.
      One is the Pixels Per Unit value, which tells Unity how large the sprites should
      appear in worldspace. Another is Sprite Mode (single vs multiple) and the Sprite
      Editor, which is particularly relevant if you have multiple sprites being provided
      from a single image file (such as an animation)
    linkText: Sprite Texture Import Settings Reference
    url: https://docs.unity3d.com/6000.0/Documentation/Manual/texture-type-sprite.html
  - heading: Humanoid Animations
    text: 3D Characters are often animated by transforming bones that are arranged
      in a hierarchy, with the root being the hips and radiating out to the the leaf
      nodes representing extremities. Each bone's transform represents its rotation
      relative to its "anchor". This means that if you rotate, for example, a shoulder,
      the entire arm attached to it will rotate. This is factored into the animation's
      data.
    linkText: 
    url: 
  - heading: Mixamo
    text: A free service offered by Adobe, there are numerous character models rigged
      for animation, as well as numerous animations. Animations give specific commands
      to specific bones, so unless two skeletons have the same naming structure,
      animations for one won't apply to the other. Unity has a way to uniformly apply
      humanoid style animations to humanoid shaped animation rigs. Please refer to
      the Canvas Page detailing the import process, particularly if you want to apply
      animations to multiple models.
    linkText: Mixamo
    url: https://www.mixamo.com/
  loadedLayout: 0
